There is not a single poll I've seen showing Palin winning this race. Not even within the margin of error. It's still a tossup between Begich and Palin on who comes in last, but all signs are clearly pointing to Peltola.

Based on 538's models. It still concludes that a big chunk of the time, Republicans win. And Google Trends tells me that among the Republican candidates in the last 7 days, Begich only accounted for about 45% of search interest and 55% went to Palin. Therefore, if a Republican is projected to win 51% of the time, 55% of 51% is 32%, but with my filtering process that I do with hurricane models, done two various ways to account for uncertainty, I have a weighted average of about 34%, which will be my new forecast.

Huge shift here from last guess, but she still has a shot...maybe. After ranked choice voting was factored in, she only lost the special election by 6000 votes. However, we could a repeat of this special election come the real midterms. Depending on Republican turnout, she could get a boost that could possibly shoot here over the 6000 votes needed. However, her unpopularity, which I saw as around 61%, is a huge problem. The surprising part of the special election was that votes where votes as the other Republican in the race as their primary choice, votes for a Democrat as their second choice. That might happen again in the general or people might change their vote knowing it might help a Democrat. Seems to depend on the Republican voters reaction to this win as well.
if she couldn't win the run off, she will not will the regular

Given her loss in the special election, we have to assume losing is the base case. What changes in the general election would alter the outcome? The easiest to consider would be Nick Begich dropping out of the race. I'd give that a very low probability and Palin would still be the underdog. We should consider the influx of negative campaign materials directed at Peltola. And, we should consider the possibility of buyer's remorse among the republican voters that refused to mark Palin as a second choice.
